-- Equities in South Africa Drop, Led by Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Sasol
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-26T16:49:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-26/south-african-equities-anglogold-bhp-mtn-pioneer-sasol.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  lost 116.84, or 0.4 percent, to 31,181.38 at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg. The measure has declined 0.7 percent
in the past five days, a second week of decreases.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest gold
producer, lost 4.46 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 329.99 rand, the
lowest since Nov. 3. Gold fell as much as 1.8 percent to
$1,351.25 an ounce. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI SJ), South Africa’s
second-biggest gold mining company, declined 77 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 116.52 rand.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, snapped two days of gains, falling 4.50 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 325 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s
largest mining company, weakened 1.21 rand, or 0.5 percent, to
256.99 rand, the first daily decline in three. Copper slipped as
much as 2.3 percent to $8,150 a metric ton on the London Metal
Exchange as concerns that Ireland’s debt crisis may spread
weakened the euro, China expanded measures to curb speculation
and North Korea’s state media warned its clash with South Korea
could lead to war.  Capitec Bank Holdings Ltd.  (CPI SJ), South Africa’s second-
largest provider of unsecured loans, lost 1.50 rand, or 1
percent, to 149 rand, the first drop in three days. The bank
said it will proceed with a rights offer in which it intends
raising 1.05 billion rand ($147 million) by issuing stock to its
existing shareholders at 125 rand a share.  Kumba Iron Ore Ltd.  (KIO SJ), the iron ore-producing unit
of Anglo American Plc, declined 5 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 410
rand, snapping two days of advances. The South African
government said it wants iron ore from a disputed portion of
Kumba’s Sishen mine to be sold at cost plus 3 percent.  Mvelaphanda Resources Ltd.  (MVL SJ), the company that
controls  Northam Platinum Ltd. , rallied 2.53 rand, or 5.5
percent, to 48.25 rand, the highest since May 4. The company
said an arbitration process that held up its planned unbundling
was favorably resolved.  Optimum Coal Holdings  (OPT SJ), South Africa’s fourth-
largest steam coal exporter, added 1.33 rand, or 5 percent, to
27.85 rand. Optimum was rated “buy” in new coverage at
Deutsche Bank AG by equity analyst Tim Clark. The 12-month
target price is 34 rand a share.  Pioneer Foods Group Ltd. (PFG SJ) fell for the third day in
four, losing 50 cents, or 1 percent, to 48.50 rand. A civil
damages lawsuit against the company and Tiger Brands Ltd. by
trade union and human rights groups will go ahead even after the
Cape High Court dismissed their pre-trial application aimed at
giving them the right to bring a class-action lawsuit against
the food companies for collusion.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, snapped two days of advances, declining 3.44
rand, or 1 percent, to 326.50 rand. Prices and margins on
chemicals remain below those achieved in 2008, Sasol Chief
Executive Officer said in a speech at the company’s annual
general meeting in Johannesburg today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
